{"slug": "diviner", "root": "diviner", "category": "divination", "gloss": "a practitioner of divination", "definition": "A *diviner* is the practitioner of divination — the general name for anyone who seeks hidden knowledge through signs, lots, dreams, entrails, or spirits. The word covers the whole family the specialists divide up: the *haruspex*, the *augur*, the *geomancer*, and the dream-reader are all diviners, distinguished only by method.", "history": "The word comes from Latin *divinus*, 'of a god': to divine is to do the gods' own work, to know what is hidden from ordinary sight. Antiquity used a single broad term — the Greek *mantis*, as Christian Bull notes, was a general designation for a wide array of diviners, who could interpret signs such as the flight of birds, entrails, stars, omens or dreams. Medieval and Tudor England kept the word close to the ground in its 'cunning men,' the semi-professional healers and diviners who worked privately for a fee. The sense stayed literal longest in the water-*diviner*, still dowsing for what lies unseen beneath the earth.", "def_sources": [{"label": "Bull, The Tradition of Hermes Trismegistus", "where": "Reference"}, {"label": "Kieckhefer, Magic in the Middle Ages", "where": "Medieval magic (PDF)"}, {"label": "Etymonline, s.v. divine (Latin divinus)", "where": "Etymology reference"}], "is_keyword": false, "etymology": {"lang": "Latin", "origin": "Latin divinus 'of a god' + agent -er", "first": "late 14c.", "note": "To divine is to do the gods' own work — know what is hidden. Water-diviners kept the word literal into modern times.", "hook": "Doing the gods' job."}, "essay": null, "sources": ["Etymonline (Douglas Harper)", "Wiktionary", "classical lexica (Lewis & Short, LSJ, Bosworth–Toller)", "Ted's historical-magic DBs (WitchcraftStudiesDB, AgrippaDOP, MedievalMagicDB)"], "stats": {"flavor_total": 1, "oracle_total": 0, "in_flavor_cards": 1, "in_oracle_cards": 0, "name_match_count": 12, "by_variant": {"diviner": 1